This process resulted in the following specific suggestions that we implemented in the model:


reduced brainstem drive to the sublesional lumbar RGs was substituted with enhanced afferent input and/or changes in their intrinsic excitability (simulated as additional drives to the hind RGs);

descending control over the supralesional cervical circuitry via (tonic) brainstem drive was adjusted so that the oscillation frequency of the cervical RGs matched those of the lumbar RGs (simulated by equal drives to cervical and lumbar RGs) and to secure fore left‚Äìright alternation (reduction of inhibitory drives to cervical V0 CINs);

commissural pathways in the lumbar compartment were reorganized to secure hind left‚Äìright alternation (descending drive to V0V CINs was removed, and their excitability was altered by an additional constant drive) (Fig. 10B); and

finally, connection weights of all inter-enlargement LPN connections were set to 5% of their pre-injury values.

    An exemplary bout produced by the post-contusion model is shown in Fig. 11A1. The model progressively transitioned from a diagonal sequence gait to trot then across lateral sequence to pace and finally back to the diagonal-sequence gait. The example bout of rat post-contusion recovery (Fig. 11A2) exhibited the same sequence of gait transitions except that it starts and ends with a lateral sequence gait pattern. Note that fore and hind left‚Äìright alternation was maintained across all steps of the bouts, while the homolateral and diagonal phase differences progressively drift in parallel across the full cycle reaching their approximate initial values at the end of the bouts (Fig. 11A1,A2, bottom panels). In both cases, the fore limbs/RGs performed one more step cycle than the hind limbs/RGs (Fig. 11A1,A2, upper panels).
